B}(GT)(\partial(\widetilde{T}_{TG}(s^{\prime})))@>{\SS(GT)_{\widetilde{T}% _{GT}(s^{\prime})}}>{}>{\bf B}(GT)(p_{j}(\partial(\widetilde{T}_{GT}(s^{\prime% }))))$ 4. The ST-condition. For any $s\in\widetilde{B}_{i+1}$, $GTDT^{\prime}\in B_{j+1}(\partial(s))$ the diagram of B-carrier functions $\lx@ams@matrix@{name=CD,datameaning=commutative-diagram}{\bf B}(\partial(s))(p% _{j}(GTDT^{\prime}))@>{{\bf T}(\partial(s))_{GTDT^{\prime}}}>{}>{\bf B}(% \partial(s))(GTDT^{\prime})\\ @V{\SS_{s}(p_{j}(GTDT^{\prime}))}V{}V\\ {\bf B}(p_{i}(\partial(s)))(S_{s}(p_{j}(GTDT^{\prime})))@V{}V{\SS_{s}(GTDT^{% \prime})}V\\ @V{\cong}V{}V\\ {\bf B}(p_{i}(\partial(s)))(p_{j}(S_{s}(GTDT^{\prime})))@>{{\bf T}(p_{i}(% \partial(s)))_{S_{s}(GTDT^{\prime})}}>{}>{\bf B}(p_{i}(\partial(s)))(S_{s}(% GTDT^{\prime}))$ 5. The STid-condition. For any $s\in\widetilde{B}_{i+1}$ one has $({\bf B}(p_{i}(\partial(s)))\stackrel{{\scriptstyle T_{\partial(s)}}}{{% \rightarrow}}{\bf B}(\partial(s))\stackrel{{\scriptstyle S_{s}}}{{\rightarrow}% }{\bf B}(p_{i}(\partial(s))))=id_{{\bf B}(p_{i}(\partial(s))}$
Definition 2.6 A unital pre-B-system is called a unital B0-system if the underlying non-unital pre-B-system is a non-unital B0-system and for all $i\geq 0$, $X\in B_{n+1}$ one has $\partial(\delta(X))=T(X,X)$
Definition 2.2 A unital pre-B-system is a non-unital pre-B-system together with, for every $n\geq 0$ of an operation $\delta:B_{n+1}\rightarrow\widetilde{B}_{n+2}$
Definition 3.6 A unital B-system is a unital B0-system that satisfy the conditions $TT$, $SS$, $TS$, $ST$, $STid$ of Definition 3.1 and the conditions $\delta T$, $\delta S$, $\delta Sid$ and S$\delta$T of Definition 3.2. Equivalently, a unital B-system is non-unital B-system such that there exists a family of operations $\delta$ satisfying the conditions $\delta T$, $\delta S$, $\delta Sid$ and S$\delta$T of Definition 3.2.
Definition 2.1 A non-unital pre-B-system a collection of data of the following form: 1. for all $n\in{\bf N\rm}$ two set $B_{n}$ and $\widetilde{B}_{n+1}$, 2. for all $n\in{\bf N\rm}$ maps of the form: (a) $ft:B_{n+1}\rightarrow B_{n}$, (b) $\partial:\widetilde{B}_{n+1}\rightarrow B_{n+1}$ 3. an element $pt\in B_{0}$, 4. for all $m,n\in{\bf N\rm}$ such that $m\geq n$ maps of the form: (a) $T:(Y\in B_{{n}+1},X\in B_{{m}+1},ft(Y)=ft^{{m}+1-{n}}(X))\rightarrow B_{{m}+2}$, (b) $\widetilde{T}:(Y\in B_{{n}+1},r\in\widetilde{B}_{{m}+1},ft(Y)=ft^{{m}+1-{n}}% \partial(r))\rightarrow\widetilde{B}_{{m}+2}$, (c) $S:(s\in\widetilde{B}_{{n}+1},X\in B_{{m}+2},\partial(s)=ft^{{m}+1-{n}}(X))% \rightarrow B_{{m}+1}$, (d) $\widetilde{S}:(s\in\widetilde{B}_{{n}+1},r\in\widetilde{B}_{{m}+2},\partial(s)% =ft^{{m}+1-{n}}\partial(r))\rightarrow\widetilde{B}_{{m}+1}$,
Definition 3.5 A non-unital B-system is a non-unital B0-system that satisfy the conditions $TT$, $SS$, $TS$, $ST$ and $STid$ of Definition 3.1.
Definition 2.5 A non-unital pre-B-system is called a non-unital B0-system if the following conditions hold: 1. for all $X\in B_{0}$ one has $X=pt$. 2. for $Y\in B_{n+1}$, $X\in B_{m+1}$ such that $ft(Y)=ft^{m+1-n}(X)$ and $m\geq n\geq 0$ one has: $ft(T(Y,X))=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}T(Y,ft(X))&\mbox{\rm if $m>n$}\\ Y&\mbox{\rm if $m=n$}\end{array}\right.$ 3. for $Y\in B_{n+1}$, $r\in\widetilde{B}_{m+1}$ such that $ft(Y)=ft^{m+1-n}\partial(r)$ and $m\geq n\geq 0$ one has: $\partial(\widetilde{T}(Y,r))=T(Y,\partial(r))$ 4. for $s\in\widetilde{B}_{n+1}$, $X\in\widetilde{B}_{m+2}$ such that $\partial(s)=ft^{m+1-n}(X)$ and $m\geq n\geq 0$ one has: $ft(S(s,X))=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}S(s,ft(X))&\mbox{\rm if $m>n$}\\ ft(Y)&\mbox{\rm if $m=n$}\end{array}\right.$ 5. for $s\in\widetilde{B}_{n+1}$, $r\in\widetilde{B}_{m+2}$ such that $\partial(s)=ft^{m+1-n}\partial(r)$ and $m\geq n\geq 0$ one has: $\partial(\widetilde{S}(s,r))=S(s,\partial(r))$ 6.
Definition 4.2 Non-unital B-system data is given by the following: 1. a B-system carrier ${\bf B}$ , 2. an isomorphism $pt\rightarrow B_{0}$, 3. for every $m\geq 0$, $Y\in B_{n+1}$ a B-carrier function ${\bf T}_{Y}:{\bf B}(p_{n}(Y))\rightarrow{\bf B}(Y)$, 4. for every $m\geq 0$, $s\in\widetilde{B}_{n+1}$, a B-carrier function $\SS_{s}:{\bf B}(\partial(s))\rightarrow{\bf B}(p_{n}(\partial(s)))$,
Definition 3.1 Let $B$ be a non-unital B0-system. Define the following conditions on $B$: 1. The TT-condition. For all $GT\in B_{i+1}$, $GDT^{\prime}\in B(ft(GT))_{j+1}$ one has (a) for all $R\in B(ft(GDT^{\prime}))_{*}$ $T(T(GT,GDT^{\prime}),T(GT,R))=T(GT,T(GDT^{\prime},R))$ (b) for all $r\in\widetilde{B}(ft(GDT^{\prime}))_{*}$ $\widetilde{T}(T(GT,GDT^{\prime}),\widetilde{T}(GT,r))=\widetilde{T}(GT,% \widetilde{T}(GDT^{\prime},r))$ 2. The SS-condition. For all $s\in\widetilde{B}_{i+1}$, $s^{\prime}\in\widetilde{B(\partial(s))}_{j+1}$ one has (a) for all $R\in B(\partial(s^{\prime}))_{*}$ $S(\widetilde{S}(s,s^{\prime}),S(s,R))=S(s,S(s^{\prime},R))$ (b) for all $r\in\widetilde{B}(\partial(s^{\prime}))_{*}$ $\widetilde{S}(\widetilde{S}(s,s^{\prime}),\widetilde{S}(s,r))=\widetilde{S}(s,% \widetilde{S}(s^{\prime},r))$ 3. The TS-condition. For any $GT\in B_{i+1}$ and $s^{\prime}\in\widetilde{B(ft(GT))}_{j+1}$ one has (a) for all $R\in B(\partial(s^{\prime}))_{*}$ $S(\widetilde{T}(GT,s^{\prime}),T(GT,R))=T(GT,S(s^{\prime},R))$ (b) for all $r\in\widetilde{B}(\partial(s^{\prime}))_{*}$ $\widetilde{S}(\widetilde{T}(GT,s^{\prime}),\widetilde{T}(GT,r))=\widetilde{T}(% GT,\widetilde{S}(s^{\prime},r))$ 4. The ST-condition. For any $s\in\widetilde{B}_{i+1}$ and $GTDT^{\prime}\in\widetilde{B(\partial(s))}_{j+1}$ one has (a) for all $R\in B(ft(GTDT^{\prime}))_{*}$ $T(S(s,GTDT^{\prime}),S(s,R))=S(s,T(GTDT^{\prime},R))$ (b) for all $r\in\widetilde{B}(ft(GTDT^{\prime}))_{*}$ $\widetilde{T}(S(s,GTDT^{\prime}),\widetilde{S}(s,r))=\widetilde{S}(s,% \widetilde{T}(GTDT^{\prime},r))$ 5. The STid-condition. For any $s\in\widetilde{B}_{i+1}$ one has (a) for all $R\in B(ft(\partial(s)))_{*}$ $S(s,T(\partial(s),R))=R$ (b) for all $r\in\widetilde{B}(ft(\partial(s)))_{*}$ $\widetilde{S}(s,\widetilde{T}(\partial(s),r))=r$
Definition 2.1. Let $X$ be a scheme, a complex $T$ is called a compact generator if $T$ is perfect and, for any complex $S$, we have ${\rm Hom}_{{\rm D}^{\rm b}(X)}(S,T)=0$ if and only if ${\rm Hom}_{{\rm D}^{\rm b}(X)}(T,S)=0$ if and only if $S=0$.
Definition 2.10 ([5]). Let $X$ be a projective variety of dimension $n$. We say that $X$ is categorically representable in dimension $m$ (or equivalently in codimension $n-m$) if there exists a categorical resolution of singularities of ${\rm D}^{\rm b}(X)$ representable in dimension $m$.
Definition 2.12. A triangulated category $\bf T$ is weakly Fano-visitor if there exists a (possibly singular) Fano variety $F$, a categorical crepant resolution of singularities $\bf DF$ of $F$ and a fully faithful functor $\bf T\to\bf DF$ such that $\bf DF=\langle\bf T,\bf T^{\perp}\rangle$. Right as above, if $\bf T\cong{\rm D}^{\rm b}(X)$ for a smooth projective variety $X$, then $X$ itself is said to be weakly Fano-visitor .
Definition 2.5. A noncommutative scheme $(Y,{\cal A})$ with a morphism $g:Y\to\mathbb{P}W^{\vee}$ is called homologically projectively dual (or the HP-dual) to $f:X\to\mathbb{P}W$ with respect to the Lefschetz decomposition (2.1), if there exists an object ${\cal P}$ in ${\rm D}^{\rm b}({\mathcal{X}}\times_{\mathbb{P}W^{\vee}}Y,{\cal O}_{\mathcal{X% }}\boxtimes{\cal A}^{\mathrm{op}})$ such that the “twisted” Fourier–Mukai functor $\Phi_{{\cal E}}:{\rm D}^{\rm b}(Y,{\cal A})\to{\rm D}^{\rm b}({\mathcal{X}})$ is fully faithful and gives the semiorthogonal decomposition ${\rm D}^{\rm b}({\mathcal{X}})=\langle\Phi_{{\cal E}}({\rm D}^{\rm b}(Y,{\cal A% })),\bf A_{1}(1)\boxtimes{\rm D}^{\rm b}(\mathbb{P}W^{\vee}),\dotsc,\bf A_{i-1% }(i-1)\boxtimes{\rm D}^{\rm b}(\mathbb{P}W^{\vee})\rangle.$
Definition 2.11. A triangulated category $\bf T$ is Fano-visitor if there exists a smooth Fano variety $F$ and a fully faithful functor $\bf T\to{\rm D}^{\rm b}(F)$ such that ${\rm D}^{\rm b}(F)=\langle\bf T,\bf T^{\perp}\rangle$. A smooth projective variety $X$ is said to be a Fano-visitor if its derived category ${\rm D}^{\rm b}(X)$ is Fano-visitor.
Definition 2.4. A Lefschetz decomposition of ${\rm D}^{\rm b}(X)$ with respect to ${\cal O}_{X}(1)$ is a semiorthogonal decomposition ${\rm D}^{\rm b}(X)=\langle\bf A_{0},\bf A_{1}(1),\dotsc,\bf A_{i-1}(i-1)\rangle,$ with $0\subset\bf A_{i-1}\subset\dotsc\subset\bf A_{0}.$ Such a decomposition is said to be rectangular if $\bf A_{0}=\ldots=\bf A_{i-1}$.
Definition 3.1. We will denote by ${\cal F}$ and ${\cal E}$, the cokernel of the tautological map appearing in Eq. (3.2), respectively Eq. (3.3).
Definition 2.9 ([5]). A triangulated category $\bf T$ is representable in dimension $m$ if it admits a semiorthogonal decomposition $\bf T=\langle\bf A_{1},\ldots,\bf A_{l}\rangle,$ and for all $i=1,\ldots,l$ there exists a smooth projective connected variety $Y_{i}$ with ${\rm dim}\,Y_{i}\leq m$, such that $\bf A_{i}$ is equivalent to an admissible subcategory of ${\rm D}^{\rm b}(Y_{i})$.
Definition 3.19. Let $K^{\prime}$ be the set of strict homomorphisms of bicategories consisting of $k^{\prime}_{1}:F\Sigma[0]\to\mathcal{H}$ and $k^{\prime}_{2}:F\Sigma[1]\to F\Sigma S^{\infty}$.
Definition 2.21. Let $f:\mathcal{A}\to\mathcal{B}$ be a homomorphism between bicategories. We call $f$ to be a weak 2-equivalence if the induced 2-functor $\Pi S\mathcal{A}\to\Pi S\mathcal{B}$ is a biequivalence of 2-groupoids.
Definition 2.16 (Moore path). A Moore path on a space $X$ is pair $(\alpha,r)$ of a path $\alpha:\mathbb{R}_{+}\to X$ and its length $r\geqq 0$ such that $\alpha(x)=\alpha(r)$ for any $x\geqq r$. For a subset $B\subset X$, the Moore category $M(X,B)$ consists of $M(X,B)_{0}=B$ and Moore paths $M(X,B)(x,y)=\{(\alpha,r)\mid\alpha(0)=x,\alpha(r)=y\}$. The composition $(\beta,s)\circ(\alpha,r)=(\alpha*\beta,r+s)$ is given by $\begin{cases}\alpha*\beta(t)=\alpha(t)&0\leqq t\leqq r\\ \alpha*\beta(t)=\beta(t-r)&r\leqq t\leqq r+s\\ \alpha*\beta(t)=\beta(s)&r+s\leqq t.\\ \end{cases}$ A reduced Moore category $\widetilde{M}(X,B)$ consists of $\widetilde{M}(X,B)_{0}=B$ and Moore paths not staying put on a point of $B$, i.e. $\widetilde{M}(X,B)=M(X,B)/\sim$ where $\sim$ is the equivalence relation generated by $(c_{b},0)\sim(c_{b},r)$ for the constant path $c_{b}$ on each $b\in B$ and $r>0$. Let $(\alpha,r)$, $(\beta,s)$ be Moore paths from $x$ to $y$. A homotopy from $(\alpha,r)$ to $(\beta,s)$ is a pair $(H,\gamma)$ of a homotopy $H:\mathbb{R}_{+}\times I\to X$ from $\alpha$ to $\beta$ and a path $\gamma:I\to\mathbb{R}_{+}$ from $r$ to $s$ such that $H(0,s)=x$ and $H(v,s)=H(\gamma(s),s)=y$ for any $s\in I$, $v\geqq\gamma(s)$. A homotopy from a homotopy $(H,\gamma)$ to $(H^{\prime},\gamma^{\prime})$ between Moore paths $(\alpha,t)$ and $(\beta,s)$ is also a pair $(G,\Gamma)$ of a homotopy $G$ between $H$ and $H^{\prime}$ and a homotopy $\Gamma$ between $\gamma$ and $\gamma^{\prime}$ such that $(G_{u},\Gamma_{u})$ is a homotopy between $(\alpha,t)$ and $(\beta,s)$ for each $u\in I$.
Definition 4.11. A $\mathbf{Cat}$-graph $\mathcal{A}$ is called acyclic when $\mathcal{A}(x,y)=\phi$ if $\mathcal{A}(y,x)\not=\phi$ for each $x,y\in\mathcal{A}_{0}$, and $\mathcal{A}(z,z)=*$ for each $z\in\mathcal{A}_{0}$. Moreover, $\mathcal{A}$ is called biacyclic if $\mathcal{A}$ is acyclic and each $\mathcal{A}(x,y)$ is also acyclic. A bicategory is called acyclic (resp. biacyclic) if its underlying $\mathbf{Cat}$-graph is acyclic (resp. biacyclic).
Definition 2.3. Let $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ be bicategories. A lax functor $f:\mathcal{A}\to\mathcal{B}$ consists of the following data; 1. a map $f:\mathcal{A}_{0}\to\mathcal{B}_{0}$, 2. a functor $f_{x,y}:\mathcal{A}(x,y)\to\mathcal{B}(x,y)$ for each $x,y\in\mathcal{A}_{0}$, 3. a 2-morphism $f_{w,w^{\prime}}:f(w^{\prime})\circ f(w)\Rightarrow f(w^{\prime}\circ w)$ for each $w\in\mathcal{A}(x,y)_{0}$ and $w^{\prime}\in\mathcal{A}(y,z)_{0}$, 4. a 2-morphism $f_{x}:1_{f(x)}\Rightarrow f(1_{x})$ for each $x\in\mathcal{A}_{0}$, satisfying the coherent condition. A lax functor $f$ is called a homomorphism if each $f_{w,w^{\prime}}$ and $f_{x}$ is invertible, moreover, called a strict homomorphism if each $f_{w,w^{\prime}}$ and $f_{x}$ is an identity map. When both $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ are 2-categories, a strict homomorphism between them is called a 2-functor.
Definition 2.13. For a simplicial set $X$, the 2-categorization $c(X)$ is a 2-category defined as follows: • The set of objects $c(X)_{0}=X_{0}$. • The set of 1-morphism from an object $x$ to $y$ is generated by 1-simplices of $X$, i.e. $c(X)(x,y)=\{e_{n}\ldots e_{1}\mid e_{i}\in X_{1},d_{1}(e_{i-1})=d_{0}(e_{i}),d% _{1}(e_{1})=x,d_{0}(e_{n})=y,n\geqq 1\}$ with concatenation as the composition. For a 1-morphism $e=e_{n}\ldots e_{1}$ in $c(X)$, denote the initial point $d_{1}(e_{1})$ of $e$ by $s(e)$, and the terminal point $d_{0}(e_{n})$ by $t(e)$. • A 2-morphism from a 1-morphism $f$ to $g$ with $s(f)=s(g)$ and $t(f)=t(g)$ is an equivalence class of sequences of triple with respect to $X_{3}$ $(h_{n}\sigma_{n}h^{\prime}_{n},\ldots,h_{1}\sigma_{1}h_{1}^{\prime})$ where $\sigma_{i}\in X_{2},h_{i},h^{\prime}_{i}\in c(X)_{1}$ satisfying 1. $d_{0}d_{0}(\sigma_{i})=s(h_{i})$ and $d_{1}d_{2}(\sigma_{i})=t(h^{\prime}_{i})$, 2. $h_{1}d_{1}(\sigma_{1})h^{\prime}_{1}=f$ and $h_{n}d_{0}(\sigma_{n})d_{2}(\sigma_{n})h^{\prime}_{n}=g$, 3. $h_{i-1}d_{0}(\sigma_{i-1})d_{2}(\sigma_{i-1})h^{\prime}_{i-1}=h_{i}d_{1}(% \sigma_{i})h^{\prime}_{i}$. Note that the above equivalence relation with respect to 3-simplexes is generated by $(d_{0}(\tau)(d_{2}d_{3}(\tau)),d_{2}(\tau))\sim((d_{0}d_{1}(\tau))d_{3}(\tau),% d_{1}(\tau))$ for any 3-simplex $\tau\in X_{3}$. The vertical composition is given by the concatenation. On the other hand, horizontal composition $c(X)(f^{\prime},g^{\prime})\times c(X)(f,g)\to c(X)(f^{\prime}f,g^{\prime}g)$ is given by sending $((h_{n}\sigma_{n}h^{\prime}_{n},\ldots,h_{1}\sigma_{1}h^{\prime}_{1}),(\ell_{m% }\rho_{m}\ell^{\prime}_{m},\ldots,\ell_{1}\rho_{1}\ell^{\prime}_{1}))$ to $(h_{n}\sigma_{n}h^{\prime}_{n}g,\ldots,h_{1}\sigma_{1}h^{\prime}_{1}g,f^{% \prime}\ell_{m}\rho_{m}\ell^{\prime}_{m},\ldots,f^{\prime}\ell_{1}\rho_{1}\ell% ^{\prime}_{1}).$ A simplicial map $f:X\to Y$ induces a 2-functor $c(f):c(X)\to c(Y)$ such that $c(f)(x)=f_{0}(x)$ on objects and $c(f)(e_{n}\ldots e_{1})=f_{1}(e_{n})\ldots f_{1}(e_{1})$ on 1-morphisms, and $c(f)(h_{n}\sigma_{n}h^{\prime}_{n},\ldots,h_{1}\sigma_{1}h_{1}^{\prime})=(f_{1% }(h_{n})f_{2}(\sigma_{n})f_{1}(h^{\prime}_{n}),\ldots,f_{1}(h_{1})f_{2}(\sigma% _{1})f_{1}(h_{1}^{\prime}))$ on 2-morphisms. The 2-categorization is a 2-functor $c:\mathbf{Set}^{\Delta^{\mathrm{op}}}\to\mathbf{2Cat}$.
